$CATEGORY: ECBS5200 Pre-Work/Module 01 - Tokenization

::M01-Q1 Subword tokenization::Why do modern models use subword tokenization instead of splitting text on spaces?{
~It's faster to process subwords than whole words
=A fixed vocabulary of subword pieces can represent any word, including rare and misspelled ones
~Subwords are easier for humans to read
~It was the first tokenization method invented
}

::M01-Q2 Truncation::A consumer complaint is 200 tokens long and you set max_length\=128. What happens to the last 72 tokens?{
=They are silently dropped — the model never sees them
~They are compressed into a summary token
~They are stored separately and processed in a second pass
~The model automatically extends to accommodate them
}

::M01-Q3 Attention mask::What does the attention mask tell the model?{
~Which tokens are most important in the sentence
=Which positions contain real tokens (1) and which are padding (0)
~How much attention to pay to each word
~Which tokens were truncated
}

::M01-Q4 Special tokens::What is the purpose of the [CLS] token?{
~It marks where the text was truncated
=It marks the start of the sequence; its representation becomes the sentence-level summary used for classification
~It separates two different sentences
~It indicates the language of the input
}

$CATEGORY: ECBS5200 Pre-Work/Module 02 - Pretrained Encoders

::M02-Q1 Transfer learning::Why do we start with a pretrained model instead of training from scratch?{
=The pretrained model already understands language patterns; we only need to teach it our specific task
~Pretrained models are always more accurate
~Training from scratch is not possible with PyTorch
~Pretrained models don't need any further training
}

::M02-Q2 Classification head::What is the classification head in a text classification model?{
~The first layer that reads the input tokens
~The attention mechanism that weighs different tokens
=A linear layer that takes the encoder's output and produces a score for each class
~The tokenizer that converts text to numbers
}

$CATEGORY: ECBS5200 Pre-Work/Module 03 - Train vs Eval Mode

::M03-Q1 Eval mode::What happens if you forget to call model.eval() before running predictions?{
~The model will crash with an error
~The predictions will be exactly the same
=Dropout stays active, making predictions noisy and non-deterministic
~The model will train on the test data
}

::M03-Q2 no_grad::What does torch.no_grad() do?{
~It switches the model to eval mode
~It prevents the model from making predictions
=It disables gradient computation, saving memory during inference
~It freezes all model parameters permanently
}

::M03-Q3 Train mode purpose::Why is dropout enabled during training but disabled during evaluation?{
=During training, dropout prevents overfitting by randomly deactivating neurons. During evaluation, we want the full model's deterministic output.
~Dropout makes training faster
~Dropout is a bug that only appears during training
~It doesn't matter — dropout has no effect on results
}

$CATEGORY: ECBS5200 Pre-Work/Module 04 - Confusion Matrices & Macro-F1

::M04-Q1 Accuracy problem::You have a dataset where 90% of examples belong to class A. A model that always predicts class A achieves 90% accuracy. Why is this misleading?{
=The model has learned nothing — it completely ignores all other classes, which is useless in practice
~90% is too low to be useful
~Accuracy should only be used with balanced datasets
~The model is actually very good since 90% is a high score
}

::M04-Q2 Macro-F1::What does macro-F1 measure, and why do we prefer it for imbalanced datasets?{
=It averages F1 across all classes equally, so rare classes count just as much as common ones
~It only measures performance on the most common class
~It weights classes by their frequency in the dataset
~It measures how fast the model runs
}

::M04-Q3 Confusion matrix reading::In a confusion matrix, what do off-diagonal entries represent?{
~Correct predictions
=Misclassifications — the model predicted one class but the true label was a different class
~Missing data
~Padded tokens
}

$CATEGORY: ECBS5200 Pre-Work/Module 05 - Calibration

::M05-Q1 Calibration definition::A model outputs 90% confidence on 100 predictions. If the model is well-calibrated, approximately how many of those 100 predictions should be correct?{
=About 90
~All 100
~Exactly 90
~It depends on the number of classes
}

::M05-Q2 Overconfidence::Most neural networks are overconfident. What does this mean in practice?{
~They make too many predictions
=When they say "95% confident," they are correct less than 95% of the time
~They take too long to run
~They use too much memory
}

::M05-Q3 Reliability diagram::On a reliability diagram, what does perfect calibration look like?{
~A horizontal line at y\=1.0
~A curve that starts high and drops off
=A diagonal line from (0,0) to (1,1)
~A vertical line at x\=0.5
}

$CATEGORY: ECBS5200 Pre-Work/Module 06 - LoRA/PEFT

::M06-Q1 LoRA concept::What is the core idea behind LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation)?{
~Delete most of the model's layers to make it smaller
~Train the model from scratch with fewer parameters
=Freeze the pretrained weights and add small trainable matrices alongside them
~Use a smaller vocabulary to reduce parameter count
}

::M06-Q2 PEFT benefit::If a model has 149 million parameters but LoRA makes only 1-2 million trainable, what are the practical benefits?{
=Faster training, less GPU memory needed, and much smaller checkpoint files to save
~The model becomes more accurate
~The model can process longer text inputs
~There are no benefits — more trainable parameters is always better
}

$CATEGORY: ECBS5200 Pre-Work/Module 07 - Quantization

::M07-Q1 Quantization size::A model has 149 million parameters stored in FP32 (4 bytes each), totaling ~571 MB. If we quantize to INT8 (1 byte each), approximately how large is the model?{
~286 MB
=~144 MB
~571 MB (same size)
~57 MB
}

::M07-Q2 Quantization trade-off::What is the fundamental trade-off in quantization?{
~Speed vs. accuracy — quantized models are always slower but more accurate
=Size/cost vs. potential quality loss — using fewer bits per weight makes the model smaller and cheaper to serve, but may reduce accuracy slightly
~Memory vs. vocabulary size
~Training time vs. inference time
}

$CATEGORY: ECBS5200 Pre-Work/Module 08 - Distillation

::M08-Q1 Soft vs hard labels::A dataset says a complaint is "billing dispute" (hard label). The teacher model says "70% billing dispute, 20% payment issue, 10% account management" (soft label). Why is the soft label more informative?{
=It encodes relationships between classes — billing dispute and payment issue are related, which the hard label doesn't capture
~Soft labels are always more accurate than hard labels
~Hard labels contain errors that soft labels fix
~Soft labels use less memory
}

::M08-Q2 Temperature::In distillation, what does increasing the temperature do to the teacher's output probabilities?{
~Makes the highest probability even higher
~Converts probabilities to hard labels
=Spreads the probabilities more evenly across classes, revealing more information about class relationships
~Reduces the number of classes
}

::M08-Q3 Distillation purpose::What is the goal of knowledge distillation?{
~To make the teacher model larger and more accurate
~To combine two models into one
=To transfer knowledge from a large expensive model to a small cheap model that can be deployed more efficiently
~To remove incorrect predictions from the training data
}
